00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:03.340
The last video was very
abstract in general, and

00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:06.980
I used you know, f of x
and g of t, and h of t.

00:00:06.980 --> 00:00:09.720
What I want to do in this video
is do an actual example.

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:12.730
Let's say I have f of xy.

00:00:12.730 --> 00:00:17.325
Let's say that f of
xy is equal to xy.

00:00:17.325 --> 00:00:20.595
And let's say that we have
a path in the xy plane, or

00:00:20.595 --> 00:00:21.775
a curve in the xy plane.

00:00:21.775 --> 00:00:29.480
And I'm going to define my
curve by x being equal to

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:36.430
cosine of t, and y being
equal to sine of t.

00:00:36.430 --> 00:00:40.090
And we're going to go from--
you know, we have to define

00:00:40.090 --> 00:00:43.740
what are our boundaries in our
t --and we're going to go from

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:48.800
t is equal to 0-- or t is going
to be greater than or equal to

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:50.930
0 --and then less
than or equal to.

00:00:50.930 --> 00:00:53.340
We're going to deal in
radians, pi over 2.

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:56.370
If this was degrees, that
would be 90 degrees.

00:00:56.370 --> 00:00:57.440
So that's our curve.

00:00:57.440 --> 00:00:59.860
And immediately you might
already know what this type

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:00.770
of a curve looks like.

00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:02.900
And I'm going to draw that
really fast right here in and

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:04.110
we'll try to visualize this.

00:01:04.110 --> 00:01:06.120
I've actually drafted
ahead of time so that

00:01:06.120 --> 00:01:07.590
we can visualize this.

00:01:07.590 --> 00:01:09.530
So this curve right here, if I
were to just draw it in the

00:01:09.530 --> 00:01:13.530
standard xy plane-- do that in
a different color so we can

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:18.430
make the curve green; let's say
that is y, and this is right

00:01:18.430 --> 00:01:24.400
here x --so when t is equal
to 0, x is going to be

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:26.310
equal to cosine of 0.

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:30.620
Cosine of 0 is 1, y is going to
be equal to sine of 0, which

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:33.500
is 0, so t is equal to 0.

00:01:33.500 --> 00:01:37.650
We're going to be at x equal to
1, that's cosine of 0, and y is

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:39.706
sine of 0, or y is going to
be 0, so we're going

00:01:39.706 --> 00:01:40.500
to be right there.

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:44.380
That's what t is equal
to; t is equal to 0.

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:46.990
When t is equal to pi of 2,
what's going to happen?

00:01:46.990 --> 00:01:50.000
Cosine of pie over 2--
that's the angle; cosine

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.270
of pi over 2 --is 0.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:55.010
Sine of pi over 2 is 1.

00:01:55.010 --> 00:01:57.270
We're going to be
at the point 0, 1.

00:01:57.270 --> 00:02:01.410
So this is when we're at
t is equal to pi over 2.

00:02:01.410 --> 00:02:03.340
You might recognize what we're
going to draw is actually the

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:07.080
first quadrant of the unit
circle; when t is equal to pi

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:11.530
over 4, or 45 degrees, we're
going to be at square root

00:02:11.530 --> 00:02:12.240
of 2, square root of 2.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:13.860
You can try it out for
yourself, but we're just

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:15.360
going to have a curve
that looks like this.

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:18.050
It's going to be the
top right of a circle,

00:02:18.050 --> 00:02:18.915
of the units circle.

00:02:18.915 --> 00:02:20.280
It's going to have radius 1.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:22.670
And we're going to go in that
direction, from t is equal to

00:02:22.670 --> 00:02:25.830
0, to t is equal to pi over 2.

00:02:25.830 --> 00:02:28.300
That's what this
curve looks like.

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:32.240
But our goal isn't here just to
graph a parametric equation.

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:36.680
What we want to do is raise a
fence out of this kind of base

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:38.685
and rise it to this surface.

00:02:38.685 --> 00:02:41.570
So let's see if we can do that
or at least visualize it first,

00:02:41.570 --> 00:02:44.740
and then we'll use the tools
we used in the last video.

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:51.210
So right here I've graphed this
function, and I've rotated it a

00:02:51.210 --> 00:02:52.230
little bit so you can
see [UNINTELLIGIBLE]

00:02:52.230 --> 00:02:53.010
case.

00:02:53.010 --> 00:02:56.080
This right here-- let me get
some dark colors out --that

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:01.680
right there is the x axis, that
in the back is the y axis, and

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:03.560
the vertical axis
is the z axis.

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:07.330
And this is actually 2, this
is 1 right here, y equal 1

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:09.310
is right there, so this
is graphed that way.

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:12.030
So if I were to graphs this
contour in the xy plane, it

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:14.900
would be under this graph and
it would go like something like

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:18.110
this--- let me see if I can
draw it --it would look

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:18.730
something like this.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:20.800
This would be on the xy plane.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:25.300
This is the same exact graph,
f of x is equal to xy.

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:30.080
This is f of x; f of
xy is equal to xy.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:32.480
That's both of these,
I just rotated it.

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:37.170
In this situation that right
